1 dollars, which may be increased by up to five percent annually; to collect the processing fees
2 charged by the state or federal government for a criminal history record check; and to collect
3 fees charged by sheriffs and third-party vendors for fingerprinting; and
4 WHEREAS, legislators have heard from constituents who are concerned about the
5 costs associated with background checks, and there is interest in determining the costs of
6 background checks for teachers and other school employees, who pays these costs, how the
7 payment of these costs is handled by school governing authorities across the state, and if
8 there are ways to defray such costs if borne by teachers or other school employees.
9 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
10 Legislature of Louisiana does hereby urge and request the state Department of Education to
11 study the costs associated with criminal background checks for teachers and other school
12 employees and to submit a written report of findings and conclusions, including any
13 recommendations for related legislation, to the House Committee on Education not later than
14 March 1, 2027.
15 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the study shall include, at a minimum, the costs
16 associated with criminal background checks required by law for the certification and
17 employment of teachers and other school employees, who pays these costs, how the payment
18 of these costs is handled by school governing authorities across the state, and if there are
19 ways to defray such costs if borne by teachers or other school employees.
20 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the department may seek input from the
21 legislative auditor relative to this study.
